Based on the code and the command line, it is clear that the root cause of the bug is the attempt to set the Exif tag value outside its valid range.

The minimal local fix is to restrict the range of values that can be set for the Exif tag. For example, in the CanonCs class definition, you could add the following code:
```cpp
class CanonCs {
    //...
    int maxAperture = 90; // restrict the maximum aperture value
    //...
};
```
However, a more thorough root-cause fix would be to add validation for the Exif tag values before attempting to set them. This could be done in the Exif class by adding the following code:
```cpp
class Exif {
    //...
    void setTag(const std::string& tagName, const std::string& value) {
        if (tagName == "CanonCs") {
            int val = std::stoi(value);
            if (val < 65 || val > 90) {
                throw std::invalid_argument("Invalid value for Exif tag CanonCs");
            }
        }
        //...
    }
    //...
};
```
This code checks if the tag name is "CanonCs" and if the value is within the valid range before attempting to set the tag.

